[3] Israel (Jerusalem)
Date: Thu 7 May 2020
Source: CIDRAP [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/05/news-scan-may-07-2020


An investigation into a large measles outbreak in Israel's Jerusalem district in 2018 and 2019 revealed challenges with contact tracing and isolating patients, due to high population density, and that vaccination encouragement from rabbis helped turn the tide. The team reported its findings today [7 May 2020] in a Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR) note from the field [see citation below].

The outbreak began following imported cases, mainly from Ukraine, in March 2018 in Central and Northern districts of Israel, but it spread to Jerusalem in August 2018 because of 2 unvaccinated infected people, a 20-year-old boarding school student and a 2-year-old child. The outbreak spread rapidly though densely populated low-income orthodox Jewish neighborhoods where 1st-dose measles vaccine coverage is lower than for children in other communities.

Transmission intensified during the fall Jewish high holidays. Investigators found inadequate adherence to isolation recommendations among patients and their parents and were challenged by high numbers of close contacts to track.

The response also included postexposure prophylaxis and a vaccine campaign that targeted children ages 1-14 years old. High numbers of cases and the impact on young children triggered community concerns, and the rabbi community helped support the vaccine campaign, which encouraged acceptance and compliance with control activities.

Vaccine coverage climbed from 76.3% to 96.8%, and by December 2018, cases dropped considerably, ending in May 2019. The outbreak totaled 4115 cases, about half from Jerusalem.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall <mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Citation. Stein-Zamir C, Abramson N, Shoob H. Notes from the Field: Large Measles Outbreak in Orthodox Jewish Communities -- Jerusalem District, Israel, 2018-2019. MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep 2020;69:562-563. DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.15585/mmwr.mm6918a3external icon. - Mod.LK

